Attenuation Experiments : At atmospheric pressure, Alpha particles are rapidly
attenuated. Students place the source at varying distances from the detector, and
record the centroid channel to study this. Similarly, the effect of air pressure is
studied by setting different levels of vacuum for a constant source-detector distance
Non-Enriched Sources : Thorium Nitrate is easily available from chemical suppliers,
and we can use electrolysis ( 20mA, 10 minutes for a 5gm/5gm aqueous solution ) to
deposit a thin film of Bismuth-212 on lead foils used as electrodes. The short half life
of Bi-212 (60.5 minutes) enables students to view the typical exponential decay
curve within one lab session by studying the activity of the film deposited on the
Anode. 212-Bismuth's decay chain involves two distinct alpha particle energies,
with the highest known branching ratio of 66:34, and this can also be verified to
better than 1% accuracy with our spectrometer.
